    <h2>Special Situations</h2>

    <h3>First-time buyers with limited credit history</h3>
    <p>Auto lenders often have special programs for first-time buyers, sometimes called "first time buyer programs" or "tier 1 credit builder programs." These come with higher rates but are accessible with limited credit history. Income documentation is particularly important for these applicants since credit history cannot compensate for income uncertainty.</p>

    <h3>Buying from a private party</h3>
    <p>Private party purchases require obtaining a loan independently rather than through a dealer. Your bank or credit union is the primary option. Documentation requirements are the same as for bank-direct auto loans: pay stubs, bank statements, proof of insurance, and vehicle information for the lender to process the loan and lien.</p>

    <h3>Lease vs. purchase</h3>
    <p>Lease applications have the same income documentation requirements as loan applications. Lease underwriting often has stricter credit score requirements than purchase financing, but income documentation standards are comparable.</p>

    <h3>Trading in a vehicle with negative equity</h3>
    <p>Rolling negative equity from a trade-in into a new loan increases the loan amount beyond the vehicle's purchase price. This creates a higher monthly payment and a higher DTI. Lenders see this frequently but factor the higher payment into their DTI analysis. If you already have tight DTI, negative equity roll-in can tip the application into decline territory.</p>

